Inquisitiveness

The Book of Mormon prophet Alma taught “faith is not to have a perfect knowledge of things...if ye have faith ye hope for things which are not seen, which are true” (Alma 32:21).

For most of our Computer Science education we have had “faith” that the big O, big theta, and big omega values we have been taught for algorithms were true. In many cases we have seen mathematical proofs to certify their correctness. We have not, in most cases, verified these efficiency measurements with raw data.

Exploration Two, Inquisitiveness, allowed us to take the next step and “experiment” to discover for ourselves the reality of these and other algorithm efficiency classifications. This process of empirical analysis involved comparing and contrasting algorithms, discovering factors that limit algorithm efficiency, and analyzing the data we collected.

Bellow is the data we collected from a few of our tests presented in more interactive medium. Click and drag rectangles on graph data to zoom in.
